Source is located as seep about 20 m upstream on hillside from lower source pool-- lower source pool was marked as main source during inventory, but WY 2018 visit marked upper source as "actual source". This is where WY 2018 took the downstream photo from, so we are continuing to monitor with this as true source. Unsure, however, if this is where 20m buffer began, so vegetation may vary, although through canyon vegetation is consistently Artemesia tridentata, Ericameria nauseosus, and Pinus monophylla.

Herd of 6 feral horses were at lower source pool when we arrived (we watched them walk to the spring from the other side of the canyon, and heard them breaking ice presumably to drink, and then ran away as we approached).

column13:
We are moving the spring source for safety reasons: According to GPS, spring source coordinates are another 1000 ft upstream, but we believe the route to get there is unsafe-- the main wash is blocked by a small waterfall jammed with boulders, and other alternative overland routes look too steep and/or crumbly with loose rock. The new monitored source emerges from the boulder jam and flows as a small waterfall into a small pool where water quality is taken. In a side canyon on River Right, marked by a dense stand of Typha, there are two large, deep pools that appears several feet deep, and we can hear the trickling of a source feeding into the pools, so unlikley they are surface water fed (are these the Latos Pools?-- could check the inventory data to see if this location was monitored originally). 

Arrived at this spring by boat.

column13:
Spring source previously monitored as hypocrene from cave/small animal burrow at base of bank within thicket of Rhus trilobata. We are keeping spring classification as hypocrene, but moving the source to be the center of a line of several medium-large (2-6 m) Chilopsis linearis which are growing in the wash. This makes more sense to us as there is no indication that any water flows in the cave or seeps out of the cliffs, and Chilopsis linearis indicate presence of moisture more than Rhus trilobata, which is the dominant vegetation within the buffer of the old source location. 
May want to revisit site with historical springs data. moj

column13: This is the first revisit since the spring was inventoried in 2016. The rainwater collector (10 m x 10 m) is well-maintained and has a rubber tarp installed over the concrete base which looks in very good shape. The three rainwater collectors all have well-maintained pipes, and the pipe that leads from the gabion wall also is well maintained and mostly covered by gravel. The pipe at the base of the gabion wall also covered in placed rocks and well-maintained. There is no sign of any seepage or moisture around the gabion wall, nor upstream of it. We also visited the hackberry cluster downstream of the tanks, and found no sign of surface water runoff. This spring was initially rejected and then accepted, seemingly because of historical documentation and possible importance in the future. However, no source was indicated to monitor-- at the gabion wall, or in the hackberries? The gabipon wall has no sign of riparian vegetation, and the site in general has the characteristics of an actively maintained sheep guzzler, not a spring that would benefit from monitoring within the scope of our desert springs protocol. Future crews may want to return every three years to visit the gabion wall, but it may be more efficient to simply ask the Society for the Conservation of Bighorn sheep if they have noticed any surface water near the gabion wall. As of now, it does not seem efficient or beneficial to continue monitoring this site.
